window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"Which of the following organisms is not a protozoan?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amoeba","B":"Ascaris","C":"Plasmodium","D":"Paramecium"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Protozoa are a group of single-celled microorganisms, which include Amoeba, Plasmodium, and Paramecium. Ascaris, on the other hand, is a genus of parasitic nematode worms, not a protozoan.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The structure of the cell membrane is a","images":[],"options":{"A":"double layer and a double protein layer","B":"middle bi-layer of protein with a lipid layer on either surface","C":"middle bi-layer of lipid with a protein layer on either surface","D":"protein layer with two inner lipid layers"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The structure of the cell membrane is a phospholipid bilayer, which is a middle bi-layer of lipid with a protein layer on either surface. This structure allows the cell membrane to be flexible and selectively permeable to substances.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following cells is a specialized cell?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amoeba","B":"Plasmodium","C":"Guard cell","D":"Meristematic cell"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A specialized cell is a cell that performs a specific function in an organism. The guard cell is a specialized cell in plants that controls the opening and closing of stomata, which are small openings on the surface of leaves that allow for gas exchange. Amoeba and Plasmodium are organisms, not cells. Meristematic cells are undifferentiated cells in plants that can divide and become any type of plant cell.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"The following organisms have structures for movement except","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amoeba","B":"Spirogyra","C":"Volvox","D":"Paramecium"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Spirogyra is a type of green algae that does not have any structures for movement. It is a free-floating algae that moves with the current of the water. On the other hand, Amoeba uses pseudopodia (false feet) for movement, Volvox uses flagella (whip-like structures), and Paramecium uses cilia (short, hair-like structures).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PROPERTIES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE LIVING CELL","question":"Which of the following statements about protoplasm of a cell is not correct? It","images":[],"options":{"A":"is a gelatinous mass","B":"consist of cytoplast","C":"doesn't have a cytoplasm","D":"has a nucleus"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Protoplasm is the living part of a cell that is often referred to as the 'life substance' of the cell. It includes the cytoplasm and the nucleus. Therefore, the statement that protoplasm 'doesn't have a cytoplasm' is incorrect.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"When a Spirogyra filament is placed in a concentrated salt solution for 30 minutes, the cell would become","images":[],"options":{"A":"plasmolysed","B":"turgid","C":"shortened","D":"elongated"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When a cell is placed in a concentrated salt solution, it loses water by osmosis, causing the cell to shrink away from the cell wall, a process known as plasmolysis. Therefore, the cell would become plasmolysed, not turgid, shortened, or elongated.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a crocodile       Use it to answer this question     Which of the labelled parts enable the animal to stay under water most of the time?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I, IV and V","B":"I, II and V","C":"I, III and IV","D":"III, IV and V"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Its transparent eyelid, the position of its eyes and the location of its nostrils adapted it to life in water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a crocodile       Use it to answer this question    Two characteristic features of the class to which the crocodile belongs are labelled.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I and II","B":"III and IV","C":"II and IV","D":"II and V"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The scaly skin and the homodont teeth arrangement are the features of reptiles.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Water and salts are both lost from the human body in","images":[],"options":{"A":"breath and sweat","B":"breath and urine","C":"breath, urine and sweat","D":"sweat and urine"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Water and salt are removed from the body during urination and sweating.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"Which of the following features could be used to determine the growth of a seedling?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Number of flowers","B":"Number of leaves","C":"Length of flowers","D":"Length of radicle"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The length of the radicle is a factor considered in the determination of the growth rate of a seedling.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The following diagrams show the sequence of events in early cell division. Study the diagram and answer this question    In which of the following cells is this division likely to take place?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Sperm cell","B":"Blood cell","C":"Muscle cell","D":"Uterine cell"},"answer":"C","explanation":"This cell division takes place in the somatic cells. These cells are not involved in the production of gametes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"A plant that commonly undergoes vegetative propagation by means of leaves is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Hibiscus","B":"Bryophylum","C":"Crotalaria","D":"Spirogyra"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bryophyllum is a plant that commonly undergoes vegetative propagation by means of leaves. Vegetative propagation is a form of asexual reproduction in plants. It does not involve flowers, pollination and seed production. Instead, a new plant grows from a vegetative part, usually a stem, of the parent plant. In the case of Bryophyllum, new plants grow from the margins of the leaves.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The diagram illustrates a part of the mammalian skeleton. Use it to answer this question      The part of the mammalian skeleton illustrated in the diagram is the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"atlas vertebrae","B":"axis vertebrae","C":"cervical vertebrae","D":"thoracic vertebrae"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The part of the mammalian skeleton illustrated in the diagram is the cervical vertebrae.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The diagram illustrates a part of the mammalian skeleton. Use it to answer this question     The function of the part labelled I is to","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"provide support to the spinal cord","B":"provide surface for attachment of the muscle","C":"carry the spinal cord","D":"articulate with adjacent vertebrae"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The neural canal carries the spinal cord, that is it allows for the passage of the spinal cord.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Blood pressure is higher in the arteries as a result of","images":[],"options":{"A":"stress","B":"contraction and relaxation","C":"blockage in the arteries","D":"presence of valves"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Blood pressure is higher in the arteries as a result of contraction and relaxation of the heart. When the heart contracts (systole), it pumps blood into the arteries, causing them to expand and accommodate the surge of blood, which results in higher pressure. When the heart relaxes (diastole), the pressure in the arteries decreases. This cycle of contraction and relaxation results in the pressure differences observed in the circulatory system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"A farmer who wants to keep seeds for three years before planting and wants to prevent them from sprouting uses.","images":[],"options":{"A":"auxin","B":"gibberellins","C":"abscisin","D":"cytokines"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Abscising is the suitable hormone for this purpose.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"A person had an accident that affected the skull but not the nose and later lost the sense of smell. The accident must have affected the","images":[],"options":{"A":"nose by extension","B":"olfactory lobes of the brain","C":"passage from the nose to the brain","D":"part of the skull near the nose"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The olfactory lobes of the brain are responsible for the sense of smell. If a person had an accident that affected the skull but not the nose and later lost the sense of smell, it means the accident must have affected the olfactory lobes of the brain. The nose by extension, the passage from the nose to the brain, and the part of the skull near the nose are not directly responsible for the sense of smell.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Ability of the human eye to focus images accurately on the retina is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"astigmatism","B":"myopia","C":"adjustment","D":"accommodation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The ability of the human eye to focus images accurately on the retina is called accommodation. This is a process by which the eye changes optical power to maintain a clear image or focus on an object as its distance varies. Astigmatism and myopia are types of refractive errors, not the ability to focus images.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"Which of the following characteristic features is not associated with monocotyledonous plants?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Well differentiated sepals and petals","B":"Presence of fibrous root system","C":"Presence of narrow leaves","D":"Floral parts are in multiples of three."},"answer":"A","explanation":"Monocotyledonous plants typically have floral parts in multiples of three, narrow leaves, and a fibrous root system. However, they do not have well-differentiated sepals and petals. Instead, their floral parts are often indistinguishable and are referred to as tepals.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The main difference between a seed and a fruit is that a fruit","images":[],"options":{"A":"is large while a seed is small","B":"has two scars while a seed has one","C":"is pigmented while a seed is not","D":"can be dispersed  by animals while a seed cannot"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Fruit bear remains of style or scar left by it while a seed does not have any such remains or scar.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following processes removes Carbon(IV) Oxide from the atmosphere?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Burning fuels","B":"Putrefaction","C":"Photosynthesis","D":"Respiration in plants"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the aid of chlorophyll pigments. During photosynthesis, plants absorb carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere and release oxygen. This process helps in reducing the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, thereby serving as a natural air purifier. Therefore, photosynthesis is the process that removes Carbon(IV) Oxide from the atmosphere.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"A student  used the following step in testing for a non-reducing sugar.   I. added Benedict's solution to the sugar solution   II. added dilute hydrochloric acid to the sugar solution and boiled it   III. added sodium hydroxide solution to the solution in II and boiled;   IV. added Benedict's solution to the cooled solution in III.  Use the information above to answer this question    Why did the student add the dilute hydrochloric acid to the sugar solution in step II? To","images":[],"options":{"A":"oxidize the sugar solution","B":"hydrolyse the sugar solution","C":"dry the sugar solution","D":"increase the volume of the sugar solution"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The dilute hydrochloric acid is added to the sugar solution to hydrolyse the sugar solution. Hydrolysis is a chemical reaction in which water is used to break down a compound. In this case, the non-reducing sugar is broken down into its constituent monosaccharides.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"A student  used the following step in testing for a non-reducing sugar.   I. added Benedict's solution to the sugar solution   II. added dilute hydrochloric acid to the sugar solution and boiled it   III. added sodium hydroxide solution to the solution in II and boiled;   IV. added Benedict's solution to the cooled solution in III.  Use the information above to answer this question  What is the importance of step II in the testing process? To","images":[],"options":{"A":"neutralize the sugar solution","B":"soften the sugar solution","C":"change the colour of the sugar solution","D":"increase the acid content of the sugar solution"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The importance of step II in the testing process to neutralize the sugar solution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"A student  used the following step in testing for a non-reducing sugar.   I. added Benedict's solution to the sugar solution   II. added dilute hydrochloric acid to the sugar solution and boiled it   III. added sodium hydroxide solution to the solution in II and boiled;   IV. added Benedict's solution to the cooled solution in III.  Use the information above to answer this question  The colour change to be observed in step IV is","images":[],"options":{"A":"blue-black","B":"brick-red","C":"purple","D":"violet"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In the test for non-reducing sugars, Benedict's solution is used. Benedict's solution is a chemical reagent that changes color in the presence of reducing sugars, such as glucose and fructose, but not in the presence of non-reducing sugars, such as sucrose. However, if a non-reducing sugar is first hydrolyzed (broken down) into its component monosaccharides by the addition of an acid (step II) and then neutralized by the addition of a base (step III), it can then be detected by Benedict's solution. The color change observed in step IV, after the addition of Benedict's solution, would be from blue (the original color of Benedict's solution) to brick-red (indicating the presence of reducing sugars, which were produced by the hydrolysis of the non-reducing sugar). Therefore, the correct answer is 'brick-red'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following organs of the alimentary canal is not correctly matched with its function?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Gall bladder-stores bile","B":"Liver -stores glycogen","C":"Appendix - releases enzymes","D":"Teeth - grind food"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The appendix is a small, finger-shaped pouch that is located where the small intestine and large intestine meet. It is known as a vestigial organ, meaning it has lost most of its original function through evolution. In humans, the appendix does not release enzymes and does not play a significant role in digestion. Therefore, the option 'Appendix - releases enzymes' is not correctly matched with its function.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"A person suffering from obstruction of the bile duct is advised not to eat fats and oil because","images":[],"options":{"A":"bile digest fats and oil","B":"fats and oil can only be absorbed when bile is absent","C":"bile emulsifies fats and oil","D":"bile adds water to digesting food."},"answer":"C","explanation":"Bile is a digestive fluid produced by the liver and stored in the gallbladder. It plays a crucial role in the digestion and absorption of fats and oils in the small intestine. Bile emulsifies fats and oils, breaking them down into smaller droplets that can be easily digested by enzymes. Therefore, if a person has an obstruction in the bile duct, the bile cannot reach the small intestine to perform its function, making the digestion of fats and oils difficult.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : ECOLOGICAL SUCCESSION","question":"A community reaches a climax when","images":[],"options":{"A":"only pioneer organisms are present","B":"new habitats are constantly being formed","C":"there is an introduction of new plants and animal species within the community","D":"the composition and size of a community remains constant  over a long period"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A climax community is the final stage of succession, remaining relatively unchanged until destroyed by an event such as fire or human interference. It is characterized by a stable and mature community where the composition and size remain constant over a long period. Therefore, a community reaches a climax when the composition and size of a community remains constant over a long period.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Which of the following components make up an ecosystem?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Decomposers, animals and non-living factors","B":"Living and non-living factors","C":"Plants and non-living factors","D":"Plants decomposers and non-living factors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An ecosystem is a community of living organisms in conjunction with the nonliving components of their environment, interacting as a system. These biotic and abiotic components are linked together through nutrient cycles and energy flows. Therefore, an ecosystem is made up of both living and non-living factors.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"The major problem experience by organisms living in small water bodies is","images":[],"options":{"A":"drying up","B":"oxygen deficiency","C":"scarcity of food","D":"wave action"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Organisms living in small water bodies are majorly threatened by the possibility of the water body drying up. This is because the smaller the water body, the more susceptible it is to evaporation and other factors that can cause it to dry up. When the water body dries up, the organisms lose their habitat and may not survive. Oxygen deficiency, scarcity of food, and wave action can also be problems, but they are not as immediate or severe as the threat of the water body drying up.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The capillarity of a soil refers to","images":[],"options":{"A":"the particle size of soil","B":"how easily water passes through soil","C":"how well water rises up in soil","D":"proportion of water a soil holds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Capillarity in soil refers to the ability of the soil to transmit water against gravity. Water moves up from the water table to the soil surface through the capillary action. This is why the correct answer is 'how well water rises up in soil'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"An organism at the start of a food chain which provides the total input energy into an ecosystem is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"sun","B":"producer","C":"consumer","D":"decomposer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In an ecosystem, the total input energy is provided by the producers. Producers are organisms that can make their own food from sunlight and/or chemical energy from deep sea vents. These are typically plants that perform photosynthesis, but can also include other organisms such as bacteria. The sun is the source of energy but not an organism, consumers eat producers or other consumers, and decomposers break down dead or decaying organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : MODES OF NUTRITION","question":"Study the diagram and use it to answer this question.    The mode of nutrition of the plant in the diagram is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"photosynthetic and chemosynthetic","B":"saprophytic and carnivorous","C":"photosynthetic and carnivorous","D":"chemosynthetic and saprophytic"},"answer":"C","explanation":"This is a structure of the pitch plant which feeds in a photosynthetic and carnivorous manner.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : MODES OF NUTRITION","question":"Study the diagram and use it to answer this question.   The structure labelled I is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"a pitcher","B":"an onion","C":"a flower","D":"a tendril"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The structure labelled I in the plant is a pitcher.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : ADAPTATION OF ORGANISMS TO HABITATS.","question":"Study the diagram and use it to answer this question.   In which type of soil is the plant found?    Soil that is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"poorly aerated","B":"waterlogged","C":"exposed","D":"nitrogen deficient"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Pitcher plant is usually deficient of nitrogen, mainly because it is normally found in a soil that is nitrogen deficient.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : CARRIERS OF MICROORGANISMS","question":"Which of the following organisms is an endo-parasite?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Tapeworm","B":"Flea","C":"Tick","D":"Aphid"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An endo-parasite is a parasite that lives inside the body of its host. Tapeworms are a type of endo-parasite as they live in the intestines of their host. Fleas, ticks, and aphids are ectoparasites, meaning they live on the outside of their host.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : TOWARDS BETTER HEALTH","question":"Oil applied to the surface of water kills the larvae of mosquitoes through","images":[],"options":{"A":"dehydration","B":"poisoning","C":"starvation","D":"suffocation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When oil is applied to the surface of water, it forms a thin layer that prevents air (oxygen) from reaching mosquito larvae that are under the water surface. This causes the larvae to suffocate and die. The oil does not dehydrate, poison, or starve the larvae.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Which of the following natural resources is non-renewable?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Forest reserve","B":"Mineral deposit","C":"Water","D":"Wild life"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A non-renewable resource is a natural resource that cannot be readily replaced by natural means at a quick enough pace to keep up with consumption. An example is carbon-based, organically-derived fuel. The original organic material, with the aid of heat and pressure, becomes a fuel such as oil or gas. Mineral deposits are non-renewable because they do not regenerate within human timescales. Forest reserves, water, and wildlife are renewable resources because they can regenerate naturally if they are not over-exploited.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Which of the following resources is non-renewable?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Forest reserve","B":"Mineral deposit","C":"Water","D":"Wild life"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A non-renewable resource is a natural resource that cannot be readily replaced by natural means at a quick enough pace to keep up with consumption. An example is carbon-based, organically-derived fuel. The original organic material, with the aid of heat and pressure, becomes a fuel such as oil or gas. Mineral deposits are non-renewable because they do not regenerate within human timescales. Forest reserves, water, and wildlife are renewable resources because they can regenerate naturally if they are not over-exploited.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Soil erosion could be prevented by","images":[],"options":{"A":"flooding a farmland","B":"cover-cropping","C":"deforestation","D":"leaving the soil bare"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Soil erosion can be prevented by cover-cropping. Cover-cropping is a farming practice where crops are grown to cover the soil rather than for the purpose of being harvested. Cover crops help to prevent soil erosion by reducing the impact of raindrops on the soil surface, slowing down the flow of water across the soil surface, and holding the soil in place with their roots.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following statements about human blood groups is not true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A is dominant over B","B":"O is recessive","C":"B is dominant over O","D":"A and B are co - dominant"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The statement 'A is dominant over B' is not true. In human blood groups, A and B are co-dominant, which means that neither is dominant or recessive over the other. This is why we can have blood type AB where both A and B are expressed. Dominance in genetics is a relationship between alleles of a gene, in which one allele masks the expression of another allele at the same locus.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following traits is not inheritable? Ability to","images":[],"options":{"A":"taste PTC","B":"roll the tongue","C":"move the ear","D":"roll the eyeball"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Rolling the eyeball is not considered an inheritable trait. It is more related to voluntary muscle control and eye movement skills, which are learned rather than inherited.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"A woman with blood group A gives birth to a child with blood group O. Which of the following blood groups cannot belong to the father?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A","B":"B","C":"AB","D":"O"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Blood group inheritance is determined by the ABO gene, which has three alleles: A, B, and O. A person with blood group A can either have AA or AO genotype, while a person with blood group O has OO genotype. If a woman with blood group A (which means she could have AA or AO genotype) gives birth to a child with blood group O (OO genotype), the father must have contributed an O allele. Therefore, the father cannot have blood group AB (which means he has both A and B alleles), as he would not be able to contribute an O allele.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"How many chromosomes will be in a gamete if the normal cell has four chromosomes?","images":[],"options":{"A":"2","B":"4","C":"6","D":"8"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In sexual reproduction, gametes are formed by a process called meiosis. During meiosis, the number of chromosomes is halved, so a gamete will have half the number of chromosomes as the normal cell. If a normal cell has four chromosomes, a gamete will have two chromosomes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"Use the diagram to answer this question.    Which of the following statement about the cross is correct","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"The gene for the spotted coat is recessive to the gen for the black coat","B":"Black coat and spotted coat are co-dominant","C":"The gene for the spotted coat is dominant over the gene for the black coat","D":"The genotype for the F1 are homozygous dominant"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The gene for the spotted leopard is dominant over the black panther.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"Use the diagram to answer this question.   What are  the genotypes of the parents if the gene for skin colour is H?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Spotted Leopard - HH, Black Panther -hh","B":"Spotted Leopard - HH,  Black Panther - Hh","C":"Spotted Leopard - Hh, Black Panther - Hh","D":"Spotted Leopard - Hh, Black Panther - hh"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The genotypes of the parents if the gene for skin colour is H are HH, hh","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"According to Mendel's first law of inheritance, segregation of genes occur when","images":[],"options":{"A":"tall plants are crossbred","B":"short plants are crossbred","C":"tall plants and short plants are crossbred","D":"plants are crossbred"},"answer":"C","explanation":"According to Mendel's first law of inheritance, also known as the Law of Segregation, gene pairs separate or 'segregate' from each other when gametes are formed. This means that each gamete carries only one allele for each inherited characteristic. This segregation of genes occurs when any plants are crossbred, but it is most noticeable when plants with contrasting characteristics, such as tall and short plants, are crossbred.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"Which of the following statements about sex-linked characters is not true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"They are usually borne on the X-chromosome","B":"They are more common in males","C":"Males are usually carriers","D":"They are not usually carried on the Y chromosomes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Sex-linked characters are traits that are determined by genes located on sex chromosomes. They are usually borne on the X-chromosome and are more common in males because males have only one X chromosome, so a single recessive gene on the X chromosome will cause the trait to be expressed. However, males cannot be carriers of sex-linked traits because they have only one X chromosome. A carrier is an individual who has one copy of a recessive allele that causes a genetic disease in individuals that are homozygous for this allele. Since males have only one X chromosome, they will express the trait if they have the gene, they cannot be carriers. Therefore, the statement 'Males are usually carriers' is not true.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"EVOLUTION : ADAPTIVE COLOURATION","question":"In explaining the term camouflage, to a class, the diagram below show four varieties, P, Q, R and S of the same species of fish living amongst water plants in a river were used.      Use the diagram to answer this question    Which of the varieties is likely to decrease most in number if a predatory fish is introduced into the river?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"P","B":"Q","C":"R","D":"S"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The R-fish does not really have a colour that blends with the plants. This will expose it to predators.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"EVOLUTION : ADAPTIVE COLOURATION","question":"In explaining the term camouflage, to a class, the diagram below show four varieties, P, Q, R and S of the same species of fish living amongst water plants in a river were used.      Use the diagram to answer this question  Which of the varieties is most likely to outlive the others?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"P","B":"Q","C":"R","D":"S"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The varieties which is most likely to outlive the others is Q. Q looks most likely as the plants in the habitat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2015>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2015","type":"Objective","topic":"EVOLUTION : ADAPTIVE COLOURATION","question":"In explaining the term camouflage, to a class, the diagram below show four varieties, P, Q, R and S of the same species of fish living amongst water plants in a river were used.      Use the diagram to answer this question  The  variety selected in the above question will outlive the others because the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"variety is the most beautiful","B":"variety does not have markings","C":"markings of the variety are similar to those of the environment.","D":"predator does not like eating the variety."},"answer":"C","explanation":"Q looks most likely as the plants in the environment. Hence it will blend with the colour of the plants and this will protect it from predators.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];